  "text": "Taken together, these observations suggest that PARP-1 inhibition increases TCF7L2-mediated GLP-1 production. Therefore, pharmacologic PARP-1 inhibition may represent an avenue for therapeutic intervention for T2D. The classical dipeptidyl peptidase-4 (DPP-IV) inhibitors that protect the GLP-1 peptide from degradation have been used successfully as therapeutic reagents for T2D [CITATION_1] . Our studies suggest a novel mechanism by which the PARP-1 inhibitor, Olaparib, effectively enhances GLP-1 activity in the setting of hyperglycemia and could represent an alternative therapeutic avenue to that of DPP-IV inhibition for T2D.",
